

Git and GitHub Advanced Challenge Week 4

This repository contains the documentation and practical implementation of advanced Git concepts required for DevOps workflows.

Task 1: Working with Pull Requests

Scenario: Forking a repository and managing a feature through a Pull Request.
```bash
git clone <your-forked-repo-url>
cd <repo-name>
git checkout -b feature-branch
echo "New Feature" >> feature.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Added a new feature"
git push origin feature-branch

```

Task 2: Undoing Changes - Reset and Revert
Scenario: Managing accidental commits using different reset modes and safe reverts.
```bash
echo "Wrong code" >> wrong.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Committed by mistake"

Soft Reset: keeps changes staged
git reset --soft HEAD~1

Mixed Reset: unstages changes but keeps files
git reset --mixed HEAD~1

Hard Reset: removes all changes
git reset --hard HEAD~1

Revert: safely undoes a commit by creating a new one
git revert HEAD

```

Task 3: Stashing - Save Work Without Committing
Scenario: Saving uncommitted work temporarily to switch branches.
```bash
echo "Temporary Change" >> temp.txt
git add temp.txt
git stash
git checkout main
git stash pop

```

Task 4: Cherry-Picking - Selectively Apply Commits
Scenario: Applying a specific bug fix commit from another branch.
```bash
git log --oneline
git cherry-pick <commit-hash>
# If conflicts occur:
git cherry-pick --continue

```

Task 5: Rebasing - Keeping a Clean Commit History
Scenario: Updating a feature branch without creating extra merge commits.
```bash
git fetch origin main
git rebase origin/main
# If conflicts occur:
git rebase --continue

```

Task 6: Branching Strategies
Scenario: Implementing real-world DevOps branching workflows.
```bash
git branch feature-1
git branch hotfix-1
git checkout feature-1

```

